## Technical notes

**Calculating Mardi Gras:** Easter follows the Computus algorithm. Mardi Gras is always 47 days before Easter Sunday. There are JavaScript libraries for this, or the formula can be implemented directly.

**Classification logic:**

Halves (18 days each):
- Early: Feb 3–20
- Late: Feb 21–Mar 9

Thirds (12 days each):
- Early: Feb 3–14
- Kinda in the Middle: Feb 15–26
- Late: Feb 27–Mar 9

Fourths (9 days each):
- Very Early: Feb 3–11
- Early: Feb 12–20
- Late: Feb 21–Mar 1
- Very Late: Mar 2–9

Mood (same as Fourths):
- Blink and you'll miss it: Feb 3–11
- Plenty of time: Feb 12–20
- Endless Carnival: Feb 21–Mar 1
- Are we still doing this?: Mar 2–9

**No backend required.** All calculations happen client-side.

## Hosting & deployment

**Repository:** Public GitHub repo (e.g., `andrewedunn/is-mardi-gras-early`)

**Hosting:** Netlify, deployed from the GitHub repo. Or github pages with a custom domain.

**Domain:** ismardigrasearly.com

## Out of scope

- User accounts
- Sharing/social features
- Historical Mardi Gras data (pre-2026)
- Multiple cities (New Orleans only)
- Parade schedules or other Carnival info

## Success

Someone in New Orleans can pull this up on their phone during a January conversation, type in the year, and settle the question with authority.
